  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering Statute)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Monetary Transaction in Criminally Derived Property)\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- These typically mirror federal regulations and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose civil and criminal penalties for violations\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system.",
